message.content:
{
  "session": [
    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Let's have a quick MCQ session on FORCE AND MOTION."
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "According to Aristotle, what is the natural state of earthly bodies? A) Movement, B) Rest, C) Both movement and rest, D) Instant acceleration."
    },
    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "B) Rest."
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Great job! The correct answer is indeed B) Rest. Aristotle believed that the natural state of earthly bodies is rest, and a force is needed to change that state."
    },
    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Okay, next!"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "What did Galileo propose about the state of a body in motion? A) It will continue moving only if acted upon by a force, B) It will eventually stop, C) It does not move at all, D) It continuously accelerates."
    },
    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "I think the answer is A) It will continue moving only if acted upon by a force."
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Absolutely correct! A) It will continue moving only if acted upon by a force is the right choice. Galileo stated that a body in motion remains in motion until an external force acts on it."
    },
    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Got it, let’s move on!"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "What property of bodies is defined as their resistance to change in motion? A) Force, B) Acceleration, C) Friction, D) Inertia."
    },
    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Inertia is the answer!"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "That's right! Inertia is the property that causes bodies to resist changes in their state of motion. Well done!"
    },
    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Next question, please."
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "When objects of different masses are dropped from the same height in a vacuum, what happens? A) The heavier one falls faster, B) They fall at the same rate, C) The lighter one falls faster, D) They stop mid-air."
    },
    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "I believe the answer is A) The heavier one falls faster."
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Not quite! The correct answer is B) They fall at the same rate. Galileo showed that in a vacuum, all objects fall at the same rate regardless of their mass."
    },
    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Oh, I see! Let's go to the last question."
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "What is the term used by Aristotle for motion that requires a force to change the natural state of rest? A) Natural motion, B) Uniform motion, C) Violent motion, D) Inertia."
    },
    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "I think it's C) Violent motion."
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Excellent! You got it right! C) Violent motion is indeed what Aristotle called the motion that requires an external force to overcome the natural state of rest."
    },
    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That was fun! I'm finished now."
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I'm glad you enjoyed the session! Great job answering those questions! Keep up the good work!"
    }
  ]
}

{
